label.value: Anterior Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

value.value: The cusp of the pulmonic valve that has no attachment to the cardiac septum.

label.value: Left Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

value.value: The cusp of the pulmonic valve attached to the left side of the cardiac septum.

label.value: Right Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

value.value: The cusp of the pulmonic valve attached to the right side of the cardiac septum.
A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid bone to the capitate bone.
A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid, lunate, and capitate bones.
A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid bone to the trapezium bone.
A type of angiography in which motion picture camera technology is used to record the passage of dye (usually fluorescent) through blood vessels and the heart.
Any nerve outside the brain or spinal cord that connects with peripheral receptors or effectors.

A species of anaerobic, Gram negative, non-spore-forming and non-motile coccobacilli shaped bacterium in the family Veillonellaceae isolated from the human gastrointestinal tract. A. intestini is oxidase- and catalase-negative and negative for gelatinase and nitrate-reduction tests.
A species of filamentous fungi in the order Mucorales that is one of the causative agents of mucormycosis in humans.
A species of dematiaceous anamorphic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with smooth, hyaline, branched, septate hyphae.
A species of geophilic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with thin-walled, elongate, ellipsoidal macroconidia having 3 to 6 septa.
A species of heterothallic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with small, clavate, thick-walled conidia and usually one septa.
A species of zoophilic dermatophyte fungi in the phylum Ascomycota. This species causes superficial infections of the scalp (tinea capitis) in humans.
A species of dermatophyte fungi in the genus Arthroderma.
A species of dermatophyte fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with smooth, thin-walled, cylindrical to fusiform macroconidia. This species causes skin infections in monkeys, chickens, and humans.

A species of slow-growing filamentous fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with long, septate hyphae and conidiophores that terminate in small vesicles. This species is commonly isolated from soil and plant debris and is among the most common of indoor molds.
A species of psychrotrophic, dimorphic yeast-like fungi in the phylum Basidiomycota and genus Asterotremella found in soil and water. This species has no sexual form.
The potential space located between the parietal and visceral layers of the peritoneum.
A species of yeast-like saprophytic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with slimy masses of conidia and chains of one to two-celled, thick-walled, darkly pigmented arthroconidia.

A genus of non-enveloped single-stranded DNA viruses in the family Parvoviridae with a 21-22 nm diameter capsid and a genome of about 5.5kb. Bocaparvoviruses encode a novel protein called NP1 that is not present in parvoviruses from other genera.

A species of Gram-negative, oxidase- and catalase-positive, nonsporulating, short motile rod-shaped bacteria in the family Alcaligenaceae. Poultry species act as a reservoir for B. hinzii. Transmission to humans is rare, mostly occurring through occupational exposure.

A species of Gram-negative, coccobacillus-shaped, non-spore-forming, non-motile, facultatively anaerobic bacteria in the family Alcaligenaceae that is able to reduce selenate to elemental selenium. B. petrii is unable to utilize carbohydrates as a carbon source.

A species of fungi in the family Trichocomacae characterized by broadly ellipsoidal to lemon-shaped conidia, loosely branched conidiophores and phialides with pointed tips. B. spectabilis is strongly heat-resistant and is a common contaminant of heat-treated foods and juices.
A species of yeast in the family Trichocomacae that is capable of utilizing methanol as a carbon source.

A species of commensal yeast in the family Trichocomaca that are found in cheese, dairy products and the environment. It is rarely recovered from clinical specimens, usually associated with skin. C. famata is negative for fermentation on lactose and galactose.

A species of yeast in the family Trichocomaceae. Clinical isolates of C. inconspicua has been obtained from human immunodeficiency virus-infected patients with either oral or esophageal infections, women with vaginal infections, and patients with diabetes mellitus.

A species of yeast in the family Trichocomaceae. C. sake is rarely pathogenic but has been identified as a causative agent of spondylodiscitis, fungal endocarditis, peritonitis, and bloodstream infection.
A species of saprobic mushroom-forming fungi in the family Psathyrellaceae.
A potent fungal metabolite isolated from Penicillium wortmannin that selectively inhibits phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase and affects the signal transduction pathway. (NCI)
The tissue that lines the wall of the abdominal cavity, intestine, mesentery, and pelvic organs. It consists of the parietal peritoneum and the visceral peritoneum.

A species of non-motile, catalase-positive, non-lipophilic, pleomorphic coryneform bacteria in the family Corynebacteriaceae that are aerobic or facultatively anaerobic. The species is positive for utilization of fructose, glucose, maltose, and sucrose. C. aurimucosum is positive for alkaline phosphatase but negative for acid phosphatase, lipase, alpha- and beta-glucosidase, and alpha- and beta-galactosidase.
A variety of Cryptococcus albidus that is characterized by its ability to assimilate lactose, but not galactose.
A species of yeast in the phylum Basidiomycota. Colonies white to cream, and fluid to mucoid. C.diffluens is associated with rare cases of skin, nail, and subcutaneous infection.
A species of yeast in the phylum Basidiomycota. This species is characterized by its ability to utilize glucose, lactose, galactose, and potassium nitrate and its inability to ferment sucrose.
A species of saprobic yeast in the phylum Basidiomycota and the family Cystobasidiaceae.

A species of gram-negative, motile, nonsporulating bacillus bacteria in the family Enterobacteriaceae. D. dadantii causes necrosis, blight and soft rot on a wide range of ornamental and horticultural host plants.
Any of the bacteria that normally or pathogenically reside in the intestinal tracts of animals.

A species of dermatophylic and anthropophilic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota. E. floccosum is the causative agent of various cutaneous mycoses, but is restricted to the cornified layers of the epidermis.
A species of filamentous fungi in the phylum Ascomycota with conidial heads and characterized by smooth ascospores. E. herbariorum is the source for aspergiolide A, an anthraquinone derivative.

A species of anamorphic, thermophilic black yeast in the phylum Ascomycota that is commonly isolated from saunas, steam baths, and dish washers. E. dermatitidis is considered a human opportunistic pathogen.
Lymphoid cell tissue in the small intestinal mucosa.
A species of saprobic fungi in the phylum Ascomycota. E. jeanselmei is the causative agent of maduromycosis, an asymptomatic disease which presents with black or brown macular lesions.

A species of filamentous fungi in the phylum Ascomycota. Infection with F. chlamydosporum is associated with superficial mycoses and keratitis in immunocompetent individuals and with invasive and disseminated infection in immunocompromised individuals.
A fungal plant pathogen in the phylum Ascomycota.

A species of filamentous yeast-like fungi in the family Endomycetaceae normally found in plant tissues, silage and soil. It is also a component of the natural flora of the human mouth, skin and gastrointestinal tract.

A species of yeast-like fungi in the phylum Basidiomycota having cell walls containing xylose and lacking septal pores. It is characterized by an optimum growth temperature of 17 C, assimilation of nitrate, and an absence of growth with lactate.
A species of Gram-negative, pleomorphic, coccobacilli bacteria in the phylum Proteobacteria that is positive for nitrate reduction and for growth with glucose, fructose, maltose, and sucrose.
A species of fungi in the phylum Basidiomycota. This species is positive for assimilation of arabinose, sucrose, maltose, galactose, and others. It is generally non-fermenting.
A species of apiculate yeast in the phylum Ascomycota that are found on dates, grapes, tomatoes, figs, and in soil. This species is only able to ferment glucose.
